### 3.1 Return Model

The return model $r_{t}$ we use in this study is $\operatorname{GARCH}(1,1)$ [2], which is widely used in financial markets analysis and defined as:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& r_{t}=f\left(x_{t-1}, I_{t-1}\right)+u_{t} \\
& u_{t}=\sigma_{t} \varepsilon_{t}, \varepsilon_{t} \sim N(0,1) \\
& \sigma_{t}^{2}=\omega+\alpha u_{t-1}^{2}+\beta \sigma_{t-1}^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $r_{t}$ is the return at time $t, x_{t-1}$ and $I_{t-1}$ are the fundamental variable and the set of information (e.g., historical return, sentiment indicators) available for prediction up to time $t-1$.
$f$ is an appropriate function for explaining future returns based on fundamental values and exogenous information.

This setting is consistent with the semi-strong form of efficient market hypothesis [9], i.e., the assumption that all publicly available information is taken into account in the asset return. $u_{t}=r_{t}-f\left(x_{t-1}, I_{t-1}\right)$ is the residual term. Furthermore, $\omega>0$ and $\alpha+\beta<1$ are necessary for satisfying the stationarity of the GARCH model. $\omega$ and $\alpha$ mean the constant volatility and the sensitivity to past return shocks, respectively. $\beta$ is the dependence on past volatility, which is necessary to replicate volatility clustering.

The expected returns $\mathbb{E}_{t-1}\left[r_{t}\right]$ and the variance $\mathbb{V}_{t-1}\left[r_{t}\right]$ are calculated as:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathbb{E}_{t-1}\left[r_{t}\right]=\mathbb{E}_{t-1}\left[f\left(x_{t-1}, I_{t-1}\right)\right]+\mathbb{E}_{t-1}\left[u_{t}\right]=f\left(x_{t-1}, I_{t-1}\right) \\
& \mathbb{V}_{t-1}\left[r_{t}\right]:=\mathbb{E}_{t-1}\left[\left(r_{t}-\mathbb{E}_{t-1}\left[r_{t}\right]\right)^{2}\right]=\omega+\alpha u_{t-1}^{2}+\beta \sigma_{t-1}^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Hereafter, $\mathbb{E}_{t-1}[\cdot]$ is the conditional expectation and $\mathbb{V}_{t-1}[\cdot]$ is the conditional variance up to time $t-1$.
